How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Finished the passwords to enter to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict us a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy General Director of Morpho, even believes that “the century will be biometric.”
Only biometry will ensure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a transverse and transnational universe as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are worried about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission of Computer Science and Freedoms has authorized 774 systems of fingerprint recognition, hand shape or hand venous network in, administrations, cantines...
“Everyone will soon be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, a consumer privacy manager at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will allow to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are the fingerprints, the hand contour and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
“For example, some people working with concrete have very damaged fingers and their footprints are unreadable,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand imply a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - you can't capture these data without knowing them - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes needs to be repeated and thus takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, such as the recognition of the face or iris (the colorful part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased precision of the sensors and the computing capacity of the computers necessary for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border stations using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” says Sridhar Iyengar, head of security research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible markers, the DNA also raises hope and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a suitcase costing €90,000 to analyze DNA samples on the place of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometry are divided into two groups: identification (recognition of one person among others) and authentication (assure that the person is the one it claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: it is necessary to confront the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) with the information that the state possesses about all citizens already registered.
This allows you to make sure that a person does not try to usurp the identity of someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We recover the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them with the photos of celebrity freely circulating on the Internet,” says Dany Nassif, responsible for commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: photograph a quidam that makes the tail in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
The authentication originally concerned physical access (border, protected locations, cantins...) or logical access (computer opening).
It has recently been added to the presence control.
"A biometric pioneer avoids the phenomenon of the friend who points for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by entering his card and putting his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the touch of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and distributors: at the time of paying in the store with his bank card, the customer does not tape his code, but puts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon come to French merchants.
Tips to Reliance Users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive in the eyes of the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometry, a customer remains in the box for thirty seconds less, it’s valuable,” the director of a large surface explains.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
“The fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are on a second basis: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, in the absence of thorough studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Specialists in privacy protection, they continue to worry.
“The progress in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the enormous amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me worse: a generalized surveillance,” says Andrew Patrick, of the Privacy Protection Commissioner in Canada.
