Scientists have just revealed how a dog's neck movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies have revealed that happy dogs move their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs move it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are differently involved in the stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was there in other species.
He added that like in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs' disordered tail movements, the researchers followed animals watching movies where other dogs were shown.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will not take a long time before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented to dogs films in which other dogs were presented – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other factor of confusion – and we were able to trade the cheek movement and present it as going more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression moving the tail to the right (from the dog's point of view moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail deviating mainly to the left (one again from the point of view of the dog that moves the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn’t think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
He rather thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you meet several times with other dogs and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience.”
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the dog species.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln discovered that the dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a joyful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “The dogs were easier to go to a robot dog when his tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is shown in the Italian study.”
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the different studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or the robots dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
