A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York has identified a new species of bosse dolphin along the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for the scientific mission at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM), returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Do you be surprised by the discovery of this new wild dolphin species?
This is a good news, but it doesn’t surprise me.
While in the past species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics enables us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
It is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology question the classification or membership of a species to a species, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified the animals, based on the morphological differences between the species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged due to the progress of genetics.
Similarly, two very morphologically close species have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific Bose Dolphins and the Atlantic Bose Whales.
Recent studies have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by the researchers, they didn’t know that it was part of a new species, present only in that place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we might be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than the local disappearance of a population of a wider species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or under extinction depending on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the Sousa chinensis species, of which the population of the new species discovered is out, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This breeding of genes limits the creation of new species.
On the contrary, closer ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can lead to the creation of new species in the future.
The sea environment is the least known environment.
It’s better to send robots to Mars than to know what’s living in the Marian cave, just 11 kilometers from the sea.
We spend more money in searching for life on other planets than in searching for marine and it’s time that it changes.
