Islamist Mohamed Morsi promised the emergence of a “new Egypt” when he gave the oath of investiture to the presidency, becoming the first freely elected president and successor to Hosni Mubarak who was expelled from power 16 months earlier.
During his deposit before the Supreme Court, Mr. Morsi also became the first free-elected Islamist president in the Arab world and the fifth head of state in Egypt since the collapse of the monarchy 60 years ago.
He swore before the 18 black-dressed judges of the court whose building on the edge of the Nile was built to look like an Egyptian temple.
“We look forward to a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” President Morsi said during the solemn ceremony broadcast live on public television.
“Today, the Egyptian people have put the foundation of a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer from the United States, from the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group considered for more than 84 years since its formation as an illegal organization and hardly repressed by the successive governments.
Hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Mr. Morsi arrived shortly after 11 a.m. local time, followed by a small convoy.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered before the Court to acclaim the new president and, standing out of the Mubarak presidential past, the traffic was only briefly interrupted to allow the passage of its convoy in the very frequent streets linking the city center to the southern suburbs.
Considered the uncharismatic “help wheel” of the Muslim Brothers, his personal prestige has greatly strengthened since his victory and his Friday speech during which he tried to present himself as the candidate not only of the Islamists but of all those who want to end the work started during the 2011 uprising against the authority president Mubarak.
“Egypt is today a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” said Morsi, in blue costume and red cravate, addressing the judges present in the decorated room of wooderies where he swore.
Later, Mr. Morsi went to the University of Cairo where he spoke his investition speech.
He was officially welcomed by a military fanfare who played the national hymn while he was taking the guard.
Marshal Hussein Tantaoui attended the ceremony.
