He walks in the mole, the jungle and crosses the rivers to offer free medical assistance.
Dr. Georges Bwelle gives free health care in Cameroon villages
Dr Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this country of West Africa, just 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, to choose him “CNN Hero of the Year.”
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alter the periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and went to hospitals that were not equipped to come to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma of which he was going to carry the sequences for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurochirurgs in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he got any treatment he could benefit from.
“It’s not easy,” adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 p.m., go to the hospital to be the first, and you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People may die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon there is only 1 doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroons could not pay for the consultation.
Two in five people in the country live below the poverty threshold, and three-quarters of the country’s health expenditure is made in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Dr Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team practiced more than 700 free surgical acts over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital of Yaoundé.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas during the weekend to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they sit down in shells after fixing medical equipment on the roof and pass through difficult land to get to the villages that are most in need of help.
Luck doesn’t always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or mole trails.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle – with his great smile and overwhelming energy – is more than happy to join the holidays.
The next morning, the team began receiving hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people each visit,” Mr. Bwelle said.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive bequels, a pair of gloves collected or a free birth certificate – the necessary document to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, municipality or home; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the awakening room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the electric group lighting, the operation room and the material sterilization, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
This is an exciting pace, but the village musicians generally help the team to stay motivated.
“They hit the bubbles all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work,” Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work she has done.
The group, composed of Cameroon doctors and medical students, practiced 700 free surgical acts over the past year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference for those to whom they come to help.
A man explained that the free operation he had suffered to cure a hernia would allow him to work again.
“This will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to living this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works the night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
This is the second job, he explains, which funds 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer within Dr. Bwelle’s group.
He is always in the hospital or is trying to find money for his association so that he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity for field learning that they don't have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help spong blood or send the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” Ms. O’Malley explained.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their retirement, transport and education are supported by Dr. Bwelle.
“It’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” Katie O’Malley said.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroon people is not near to disappear.
For Dr Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happy by keeping the promise he has made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle added.
I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons that push me to do that.
